subject_prompt_600:
Shane Withington was born on 14 September 1950 in Sheffield, England. In 1980, at age 20, he received his Bachelor of Science from Sheffield Hallam University. He studied English Literature and Political Philosophy at the University of York, and earned a Doctorate of Letters and an MA in Political Theory at Queen Mary, University of London. Between 1987-1989, he served as a staff writer for National Review.
His academic work has appeared in the Quarterly Journal of Speech (2005), Journal of Applied Symbolic Logic (2006) and The Oxford Handbook of International Law (2007). He is the co-author, with Michael Oakeshott, of A Concise Encyclopedia of Global Legal Thought (2012). He was a member of the editorial board of the journal New Ideas (1988-1994), where he edited a special volume entitled "The Politics of Globalisation." As a member of the British Academy, he received its Lifetime Achievement Award in 1997.
On 21 October 2012, Mr. Withington passed away, aged 63, in his home near Sheffield. From 1989-1998, he worked as a Lecturer at the Institute of Contemporary Arts, London. He also taught courses at the University of Bradford, Durham University and the University of Central Lancashire. He received a Masters of Philosophy (1990) and Doctorates in Politics and International Relations (1993, 1996).
From 1999-2009, Mr. Withington was a Senior Research Fellow at Queen Mary University, London; between 2009-2013, he was a Visiting Professor at the European Graduate School, Barcelona and a Senior Fellow at Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government.
Mr. Withington was elected a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 2005, a fellow of the Royal Society in 2008 and a fellow of the British Academy in 2010.
